The new projection configuration bindings introduce string-bearing FFI surfaces that bypass the repository's documented validation contract. This can persist invalid strings through both Python and TypeScript/Node bindings.

Full review comments:

- [P2] Validate projection spec strings at the N-API boundary — /home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/orch-0.8.20-s15d/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-napi/src/lib.rs:504-508
  When a JS caller supplies a custom `ftsTokenizer` or `vectorEmbedder` containing an embedded NUL, this conversion copies it into the Rust `ProjectionSpec` without running the binding's `validate_ffi_string` gate, and the engine then persists it in `_fathomdb_projection_registry`. This bypasses the documented AC-068 invariant that every FFI string is rejected before the writer transaction opens; please validate `name`, roles, tokenizer/embedder, and `drop` strings before calling the engine.

- [P2] Validate projection spec strings at the PyO3 boundary — /home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb-worktrees/orch-0.8.20-s15d/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-py/src/lib.rs:889-895
  When a Python caller supplies `fts_tokenizer` or `vector_embedder` with an embedded NUL, this path copies the string straight into the Rust spec and it can be stored in the projection registry. That skips the PyO3 binding's documented AC-068 validation for every FFI string before the writer transaction opens; please run the same validation for spec fields and the `drop` list here.
